But ah! 'tis heard no moreWe have had in our language no other odes of the ſublime kind than that of Dryden on St. Cecilla's day, for Cowley, who had his merit, yet wanted judgment, ſtyle, and harmony, for ſuch a taſk. That of Pope is not worthy of ſo great a man. Mr. Maſon indeed, of late days, has touched the true chords, and with a maſterly hand, in ſome of his choruſes—above all in the laſt of Caractacus;
